# Bug Found

The bug is in the initialization of `max`:

```javascript
let max = 0;
```

## Why It's Wrong

Initializing `max` to `0` causes the function to fail when the array contains **only negative numbers**, because no element will ever be greater than `0`.

**Example failure:**
```javascript
findMax([-5, -3, -10])  // returns 0 ❌ (should return -3)
findMax([-1, -2])       // returns 0 ❌ (should return -1)
```

## The Fix

Initialize `max` to the first element of the array (and start the loop from index 1):

```javascript
function findMax(arr) {
  let max = arr[0];
  for (let i = 1; i < arr.length; i++) {
    if (arr[i] > max) max = arr[i];
  }
  return max;
}
```

## Alternative Fix

Use `Number.NEGATIVE_INFINITY` as the initial value (works for any numeric input):

```javascript
function findMax(arr) {
  let max = -Infinity;
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    if (arr[i] > max) max = arr[i];
  }
  return max;
}
```

## Verification

```javascript
findMax([3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2, 6])  // 9 ✅
findMax([-5, -3, -10])              // -3 ✅
findMax([42])                       // 42 ✅
findMax([0, 0, 0])                  // 0 ✅
```

> **Note:** Both fixes assume the array is non-empty. If you need to handle empty arrays, add a guard: `if (arr.length === 0) return undefined;`

